        "content": "type: search_result\ntitle: \"10 Sci-Fi Books Similar to Dune: Must-Read Alternatives\"\nurl: \"https://screenrant.com/sci-fi-books-as-good-as-dune/\"\ndescription: \"It might not have the same slow pace as Dune, but its characters, worldbuilding, and system make it a must-read for sci-fi novel fans. Science fiction stories often have a lot of doom and gloom — The Hitchhiker’s Guide to the Galaxy takes a slightly different approach.\"\npage_age: \"March 23, 2026\"\nprofile_name: ScreenRant\nmeta_url_favicon: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/CkgFbungWnsi90fVgrGFPv3-uaqeUtDlDIk-Ycspzwo/rs:fit:32:32:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cDovL2Zhdmlj/b25zLnNlYXJjaC5i/cmF2ZS5jb20vaWNv/bnMvNjdjMmFlMDI2/NWE1MzRhZGU0ZDYy/ZGM4NzkzN2Y5MmVj/MzRiYjVlYmM3ZDM2/ZTRhMzY2NGE4Yjgw/MjZjMWVhZC9zY3Jl/ZW5yYW50LmNvbS8\"\nthumbnail_src: \"https://imgs.search.brave.com/D4XEEevFnyt7RrrZnQL5I2aJEyVpWBPNzSqYB_fXZU4/rs:fit:200:200:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdGF0/aWMwLnNyY2RuLmNv/bS93b3JkcHJlc3Mv/d3AtY29udGVudC91/cGxvYWRzLzIwMjUv/MTAvMDE0OTYyNzNf/cG9zdGVyX3c3ODAu/anBn\"\nthumbnail_original: \"https://static0.srcdn.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/01496273_poster_w780.jpg\"\nextra_snippets: \"Few science fiction books have the kind of riveting storytelling and complex worldbuilding as Dune, but some come remarkably close. With the first releasing in 1965, there are six core novels in the Dune series that were written by Frank Herbert. After Herbert’s death, his son, Brian Herbert, continued the story with an additional 20 books, which he co-wrote with Kevin J.|While the sprawling saga that comprises Herbert’s work cannot be replicated, there are other sci-fi novels that echo Dune’s world-building, ecology, and philosophy. And they're the perfect thing to tide you over while you wait for the release of Dune 3 on December 18. Science fiction stories rarely feel personal because of their vast world-building.|Empire of Silence is a fusion of space travel, politics, rigid social classes, and philosophy, much in the same way as Dune. These two novels have the same kind of weight when it comes to storytelling, but they do differ in the sense that Marlowe’s feels more personal because he is the one who tells his story. Published in 1989, Hyperion by Dan Simmons was a novel ahead of its time. Even to this day, Hyperion remains one of the most unique and layered science fiction books ever written.|It might not have the same slow pace as Dune, but its characters, worldbuilding, and system make it a must-read for sci-fi novel fans. Science fiction stories often have a lot of doom and gloom — The Hitchhiker’s Guide to the Galaxy takes a slightly different approach.\"\nhash: fa26d4fd584cfb37\nembed_ref: screenrant.com-i9R\napp_id: web\nskill_id: search",
